 Budapest, Maďarsko"},"da":{"Abt 1455–":"omkring 1455–Afdød","1455–Male":"1455–Afdød","1460–Female":"1460–Afdød","1485–1585":"1485–1585","1435–Male":"1435–Afdød","1435–1455":"1435–1455","1558":"1558","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1541":"1541","1585":"1585","1485":"1485","1460":"1460","Abt 1455":"omkring 1455","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1526":"1526","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England","Chesterfield, , Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England","chesterfield, derbyshire, england":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England","Buda, Budapest, Hungary":"Buda, Budapest, Ungarn"},"nl":{"Abt 1455–":"circa 1455–Overleden","1455–Male":"1455–Overleden","1460–Female":"1460–Overleden","1485–1585":"1485–1585","1435–Male":"1435–Overleden","1435–1455":"1435–1455","1558":"1558","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1541":"1541","1585":"1585","1485":"1485","1460":"1460","Abt 1455":"circa 1455","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1526":"1526","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England","Chesterfield, , Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England","chesterfield, derbyshire, england":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England","Buda, Budapest, Hungary":"Buda, Budapest, Hongarije"},"en":{"Abt 1455–":"about 1455–Deceased","1455–Male":"1455–Deceased","1460–Female":"1460–Deceased","1485–1585":"1485–1585","1435–Male":"1435–Deceased","1435–1455":"1435–1455","1558":"1558","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1541":"1541","1585":"1585","1485":"1485","1460":"1460","Abt 1455":"about 1455","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1526":"1526","Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England","Chesterfield, , Derbyshire, England":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England","chesterfield, derbyshire, england":"Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England","Buda, Budapest, Hungary":"Buda, Budapest, Hungary","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Boris","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Slovak: from the personal name <i>Boris</i>, which is often taken as a shortening of the Slavic personal name <i>Borislav</i>, composed of the elements <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’ (from Old Slavic <i>boriti se</i>) + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’ (from Old Slavic <i>slava</i> ‘glory’), but more probably it is an altered form of the Old Bulgarian personal name <i>Bogoris</i> (a byname from Turkic <i>bogori</i> ‘small’), borne by the king of the Bulgars (sometimes known as <i>Boris</i>) who was converted to Christianity in 864. The name <i>Boris</i> was later also borne by a Russian prince, murdered in 1015, whose baptismal name was   Roman   and who is venerated as a saint in the Orthodox Church.","Altered form of Polish, Ukrainian, and Rusyn   Borys  , a cognate of 1 above.","Slovak (<b>Boriš</b>): from a short form of any of various Slavic compound personal names, containing the element <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’, e.g. <i>Borislav</i> (see 1 above). The homonymous Sorbian cognates, <b>Boriš</b> (Upper Sorbian) and <b>Bóriš</b> (Lower Sorbian), are found in Germanized and Americanized forms, only (see   Borisch   and   Borish  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Borisenko","meanings":["Ukrainian (standard transliteration <b>Borysenko</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Borys</i> (see   Boris  ), formed with the diminutive suffix <i>-enko</i>."]},{"name":"Borish","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Myer.","Americanized form of Sorbian and Slovak <b>Boriš</b> or <b>Bóriš</b> (see   Boris   3), Polish <b>Boryś</b> (see   Borys  ), and their Germanized forms   Borisch   and <b>Bohrisch</b>.","Jewish (American): shortened form of some original eastern Ashkenazic surname, such as <b>Borishansky</b>, a habitational name for someone from the village of Borishin (western Belarus)."]},{"name":"Borak","meanings":["Polish, Croatian, and Serbian: from a pet form of any of various Slavic compound personal names, formed with the element <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’ (from Old Slavic and South Slavic <i>boriti se</i>), e.g. Polish <i>Borzysław</i>, Croatian and Serbian <i>Borislav</i> (see also   Boris  ).","Czech and Slovak (<b>Borák</b>): habitational name for someone from any of many places called with <i>bor</i> ‘pine forest’; alternatively, from a pet form of any of various Slavic compound personal names, containing the element <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’, e.g. Czech <i>Dalibor</i> (compare 1 above).","Slovak (<b>Borák</b>): nickname or topographic name from the plant name <i>borák</i> ‘borage’."]},{"name":"Borisch","meanings":["Germanized form of Sorbian and Slovak <b>Boriš</b> or <b>Bóriš</b> (see   Boris   3), and probably also of the Polish cognate <b>Boryś</b> (see   Borys  )."]},{"name":"Borys","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Alicja, Czeslaw, Feliks, Ferdynand, Iwona, Jacek, Jerzy, Karol, Kazimierz, Krystyna.","Polish (also <b>Boryś</b>), Ukrainian, and Rusyn: from the personal name <i>Borys</i>, an equivalent of   Boris  ."]},{"name":"Roman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Luis, Manuel, Carlos, Angel, Jorge, Miguel, Pedro, Francisco, Julio, Mario.","Spanish and Hungarian (<b>Román</b>); Catalan, French, English, Dutch, German, Romanian, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Ukrainian, Rusyn, Belorussian, and Croatian: from the Latin personal name <i>Romanus</i>, which originally meant ‘Roman’. This name was borne by several Christian saints, including a 7th-century bishop of Rouen, and was a baptismal name of the Russian prince   Boris  , who is venerated as a saint in the Orthodox Church. In North America, this surname is also a shortened form of Slavic patronymics like Polish   Romanowicz  . Compare   Romano  .","Americanized form of German <b>Romann</b>: variant of 1 above or from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Hrodman</i> (see   Rodeman  )."]},{"name":"Borisov","meanings":["Russian and Bulgarian: patronymic from the personal name   Boris  ."]},{"name":"Borin","meanings":["Italian (Veneto): nickname derived from Venetian Italian <i>boro</i> ‘coin’.","Italian (Friuli Venezia Giulia): nickname based on regional <i>borin</i> ‘bitter cold; north-east wind’.","Russian: patronymic from a pet form of the personal name   Boris  ."]},{"name":"Borek","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Bronislaw, Jacek, Janina, Jerzy, Kazimierz, Stanislaw, Zbigniew, Zofia, Zygmunt.","Polish: from a derivative of <i>Borzysław</i>, <i>Bolebor</i>, or some other personal name formed with the element <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’ (from Old Slavic and South Slavic <i>boriti se</i>; see also   Boris  ).","Polish and Jewish (from Poland): habitational name from Borek, so named with Polish <i>bór</i> ‘pine forest’ + the diminutive suffix <i>-ek</i>. As a Jewish name, it could sometimes also be from a Polonized form of the Yiddish personal name <i>Borukh</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":0,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1354913,"age":3,"year":"1458","julianDay":2253584,"description":"The rule of King Matthias. Cultural life of a European standard flourished in his palaces at Buda and Visegrád. For a few decades, Hungary lived on a West European standard.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1354914,"age":71,"year":"1526","julianDay":2278420,"description":"Ottoman Turks defeat forces of Hungarian king at Battle of Mohacs. The beginning of 150 years of Turkish occupation.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1354915,"age":86,"year":"1541","julianDay":2283899,"description":"Hungary was divided into three parts. The Habsburg governed the western part of the country, the central area was ruled by the Turks, and the south-east Transylvanian principality (today part of Roumania) for a long time was the citadel of Hungarian culture.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705201,"age":94,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":103,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Boris was born about 1455, in Buda, Budapest, Hungary, his father, Stanislau Boris, was 21 and his mother, Julia Liszewska, was 21. He married Augusta Mattern in 1480, in Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Chesterfield, Derbyshire, England."},"et":{"Abt 1455–":"umbes 1455–Surnud","1455–Male":"1455–Surnud","1460–Female":"1460–Surnud","1485–1585":"1485–1585","1435–Male":"1435–Surnud","1435–1455":"1435–1455","1558":"1558","1458":"1458","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","1541":"1